            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Introduction</h2>
            <p>
                Kenya continues to attract foreign investors, entrepreneurs, consultants, and international businesses seeking opportunities in East Africa's largest and most dynamic economies.
            </p>
            <p>
                One of the most common misconceptions among foreign investors is that registering a company or obtaining a business licence automatically grants the right to live or work in Kenya. In reality, Kenya's immigration laws and business registration requirements operate separately, and compliance with one does not necessarily satisfy the other.
            </p>
            <p>
                Understanding the distinction between work permits, business permits, business licences, and immigration status is essential for any foreign national intending to establish or participate in a business venture in Kenya. For a wider overview of this terrain, you may review our comprehensive breakdown on <a href="https://millardlegalpractice.com/immigration-kenya-work-permits" class="text-[#C8A96B] underline hover:text-white transition">Immigration and Kenya Work Permits</a>.
            </p>
            <p>
                This guide explains the key differences and highlights important compliance considerations for investors and employers.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 1 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Business Registration and Immigration Status Are Different Legal Requirements</h2>
            <p>
                Many foreign investors begin by registering a company in Kenya through the Business Registration Service and assume that this process gives them permission to manage or work in the business.
            </p>
            <p>
                However, company ownership and immigration status are governed by different legal frameworks. A foreign national may legally:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
                <li>Own shares in a Kenyan company;</li>
                <li>Serve as a shareholder or investor;</li>
                <li>Invest capital into a Kenyan enterprise; or</li>
                <li>Acquire interests in Kenyan businesses.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Yet that same individual may still require an appropriate immigration permit before carrying out activities that constitute employment, management, consultancy, or active business operations within Kenya. Failure to appreciate this distinction can lead to structural compliance issues and unexpected application denials, as documented in our legal update detailing the <a href="https://millardlegalpractice.com/common-reasons-work-permit-rejection-kenya" class="text-[#C8A96B] underline hover:text-white transition">common reasons work permit applications are rejected in Kenya</a>.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 2 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">What Is a Work Permit?</h2>
            <p>
                A work permit is an immigration authorisation issued by the Government of Kenya allowing a foreign national to engage in specific activities within the country. Work permits are generally issued under different classes depending on the nature of the applicant's activities.
            </p>
            <p class="font-semibold text-white">Examples include:</p>
            
            <div class="space-y-4 pl-4 border-l-2 border-[#C8A96B]/30 mt-2">
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium text-lg">Class D Permit</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Typically issued to foreign nationals who have been offered specific employment by a Kenyan employer. Applicants are generally expected to possess skills, qualifications, or expertise that may not be readily available within the local labour market.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium text-lg">Class G Permit</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Commonly used by investors, entrepreneurs, consultants, and business owners intending to engage in specific trade, business, consultancy, or professional activities in Kenya.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium text-lg">Class C Permit</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Applicable to members of prescribed professions who intend to practise their profession in Kenya and satisfy the relevant professional requirements.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p class="mt-4">
                Different permit classes have different eligibility requirements, documentation requirements, fees, and regulatory considerations.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 3 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">What Is a Business Permit or Business Licence?</h2>
            <p>
                A business permit or business licence is entirely different from a work permit. Business permits are generally issued by county governments or sector-specific regulatory bodies and authorise a business to operate within a particular jurisdiction or industry.
            </p>
            <p class="font-semibold text-white">Examples may include:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
                <li>Single business permits;</li>
                <li>Health permits;</li>
                <li>Tourism licences;</li>
                <li>Financial services licences;</li>
                <li>Industry-specific approvals; and</li>
                <li>Regulatory registrations.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                These licences regulate the business itself. They do not automatically grant immigration status or authorise foreign nationals to work in Kenya. A company may possess all required business licences while its foreign owners or employees remain subject to separate immigration requirements.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 4 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Understanding the Class G Permit for Investors and Entrepreneurs</h2>
            <p>
                The Class G Permit is one of the most relevant permits for foreign investors seeking to establish or actively operate businesses in Kenya. It is generally intended for individuals engaging in:
            </p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-2 max-w-md my-2 text-sm text-gray-400">
                <div class="flex items-center gap-2"><span>•</span> Trade</div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-2"><span>•</span> Business activities</div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-2"><span>•</span> Consultancy services</div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-2"><span>•</span> Commercial enterprises</div>
            </div>
            <p>
                Applicants are ordinarily required to demonstrate that they possess sufficient capital and resources for the proposed business activity and that their presence in Kenya will be beneficial to the country. Because immigration regulations and capital thresholds may change over time, applicants should verify current requirements before making significant investment decisions.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 5 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Can a Foreign Shareholder Work in Their Own Company?</h2>
            <p>
                This is one of the most misunderstood areas of Kenyan immigration law. Many investors assume that ownership automatically creates a right to work. In practice, ownership and employment are separate concepts.
            </p>
            <p>
                A foreign national may own a company without necessarily possessing the immigration status required to actively manage day-to-day operations, provide services, or undertake work within the business. The appropriate immigration permission will depend on the individual's role, activities, and circumstances. Investors should therefore assess immigration requirements at an early stage rather than after business operations have commenced.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 6 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Hiring Foreign Employees in Kenya</h2>
            <p>
                Kenyan employers intending to hire foreign nationals should ensure that the employee holds the appropriate immigration status before commencing work. Employers should not assume that possession of a visa automatically permits employment.
            </p>
            <p>
                Before onboarding a foreign employee, employers should generally confirm:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
                <li>The correct permit category;</li>
                <li>Validity of immigration documentation;</li>
                <li>Compliance with applicable immigration conditions;</li>
                <li>Any reporting obligations; and</li>
                <li>Ongoing renewal requirements.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Failure to comply may expose both the employer and employee to regulatory consequences.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 7 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Common Mistakes Made by Foreign Investors</h2>
            <p>
                Foreign investors frequently encounter avoidable problems due to misunderstandings regarding immigration requirements. Common mistakes include:
            </p>
            <div class="space-y-3">
                <p><strong>Assuming Company Registration Is Sufficient:</strong> Incorporating a company does not automatically grant work authorisation.</p>
                <p><strong>Commencing Business Activities Before Permit Approval:</strong> Some investors begin operating before the relevant permit is issued, creating potential compliance risks.</p>
                <p><strong>Using Inappropriate Immigration Categories:</strong> Attempting to conduct business activities while holding immigration status that does not authorise such activities may lead to difficulties with future applications.</p>
                <p><strong>Failing to Monitor Permit Conditions:</strong> Every permit is issued subject to conditions that must be observed throughout its validity period.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 8 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Permit Conditions Must Be Respected</h2>
            <p>
                Obtaining a permit is only the first step. Permit holders are expected to comply with the conditions attached to their immigration status as well as any obligations imposed under Kenyan law. Depending on the permit class, restrictions may apply regarding employment activities, business operations, reporting duties, duration of stay, or sponsorship arrangements.
            </p>
            <p>
                Non-compliance may result in enforcement action, cancellation, revocation, refusal of renewal, or other legal consequences.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 9 -->
        <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl mb-4 text-[#C8A96B]">Practical Steps Before Investing or Relocating to Kenya</h2>
            <p>
                Before establishing a business or relocating to Kenya, foreign investors should consider:
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
                <li><strong>Evaluating Immigration Requirements Early:</strong> Immigration planning should form part of the investment strategy from the outset.</li>
                <li><strong>Identifying the Correct Permit Category:</strong> The appropriate permit will depend on the proposed activities and business structure.</li>
                <li><strong>Reviewing Corporate Structures:</strong> Company ownership structures should be assessed together with immigration considerations.</li>
                <li><strong>Understanding Regulatory Approvals:</strong> Different sectors may require additional licences, registrations, or approvals.</li>
                <li><strong>Monitoring Compliance Obligations:</strong> Immigration compliance should be viewed as an ongoing responsibility rather than a one-time application process.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQs -->
        <div class="pt-6 space-y-6">
            <h2 class="serif text-3xl text-[#C8A96B]">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            
            <div class="space-y-4">
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium">Does registering a company in Kenya automatically give me a work permit?</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-1">No. Company registration and immigration status are separate legal requirements. Foreign nationals may still require an appropriate work permit before engaging in business activities.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium">Can I own a Kenyan company without living in Kenya?</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-1">In many cases, yes. Company ownership does not necessarily require residence in Kenya, although immigration requirements may apply if you intend to work or manage operations locally.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium">What permit do investors commonly apply for?</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-1">Many investors and entrepreneurs utilise the Class G Permit, although the appropriate permit depends on the nature of the proposed activities.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium">Can a foreign employee start work while a permit application is pending?</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-1">Employers and employees should carefully assess applicable immigration requirements before commencing employment and should ensure compliance with Kenyan immigration laws.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-white font-medium">Can a work permit be revoked?</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-1">Yes. Failure to comply with permit conditions or applicable legal requirements may result in revocation, cancellation, or refusal of renewal.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

